 placement in federal detention, followed by their appearance in deportation proceedings and release from custody, and, finally, ending with their struggle to build new lives in the United States. This book shows how the U.S. government got into the business of detaining children and what we can learn from this troubled history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCentral AmericanszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aIllegal alien childrenxGovernment policyzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aImmigration enforcementzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aJuvenile detentionzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aMexicanszUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aNoncitizen childrenxGovernment policyzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aUnaccompanied immigrant childrenxGovernment policyzUnited StatesvCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh  aborder control.  acentral american immigrant children.  adeporting children.  adetaining children.  adocumented immigrants.  aice detaining kids.  aice detention.  aillegal immigrants.  aimmigrant children in federal custody.  aimmigration and customs enforcement.  aimmigration.  ajuvenile detention at borders.  amexican immigrant children.  asocial science.  aunaccompanied children at the border.  aunaccompanied minor immigrants.  aundocumented immigrants.  aus border control.  aus border patrol.  ayoung illegal immigrants.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z97831106211120 cprintz978052028148640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096144940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520961449423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520961449/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_